Facebook plans to scrutinize facts to limit the number of fake news
Facebook will be sending more potentially fake articles to check third parties and view findings under the original posts in an effort to combat the so-called "fake news," the largest social network said on Thursday.
The company writes in a statement on its website that it will start using up-to-date machine learning to detect possible hoaxes, which it will send to third parties for verification and potentially display the survey results below the original contributions.
Facebook has been described as one of the main sources of fake news, and many believe that these unconfirmed reports influenced the presidency's election for last year.
There are political debates about the matter in Europe. French voters are inundated with an avalanche of false news about the presidential election in May, and Germany plans to impose a fine on the social media network ahead of the September elections in advance if it does not promptly remove angry contributions.
Facebook said in a statement issued in Germany on Thursday that it was preparing to launch a new feature of the check on the review in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
"In addition to showing messages authenticated by third-party, people are asking for more content to be better informed and to make the right choice to decide what they can share," Sara Su, a product news executive at Facebook, said on her blog.
