Get to know the plant with one click.
Students with herbarian creation as well as ordinary plant lovers will be helped by the new free application Pl@ntNet.
When they're interested in what plant they've just come across on a walk, this app will advise them.
All they'll have to do is photograph the plant, and the app will recognize what kind it is.
The new app, which is available for both iOS and Android, was presented on Tuesday by representatives of the CEEV Ethics and Environmental Education Centre in Bratislava's Mountain Park as part of the Secret Life of the City project.
The project was also joined by pupils from 50 Czech and Slovak schools, who photographed and added plants from their surroundings with the app's teachers to the app database.
The newly created French app is free to download on the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of the French programmers was for as many people as possible to contribute to the app with their images, thereby increasing the number of plants that the application can recognize.
"Already children who hold a tablet or mobile phone in their hand can go to the forest," said this project's coordinator, Ivana Poláčková.
Based on a high-quality photo of the flower, leaf or the fruit of the plant, the application can recognize its name in seconds, which is then added to the photograph in both Czech and Slovak.
The French allowed us to translate the app into the Secret Life of the City project into Slovak and Czech.
It is therefore welcome that users should contribute to the app after opening an account with a picture of a plant that is not yet found in the database.
"The French will evaluate whether it is beneficial and then add it to the database," Poláčková informed.
GMB's concerns about investing in the McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union is demanding assurances from the managers of the biscuit maker McVitie's about the long-running commitment to the factory in Glasgow.
The Scottish GMB union said the company was silent for the time being about any investment in the Tollcross factory.
The factory employs more than 500 employees who produce, among other products, the Hobnob and Rich Tea biscuits.
The owner of McVitie's, Pladis, said it had invested more than £5 million in the entire area in the previous few years.
It added that the employees and representatives of the unions would be "between the first informed" in the event of changes to the operation of the factory.
In a letter to the building company, the Scottish GMB unions expressed their fears that McVitie's would "not get its promises to finance and upgrade production lines."
GMB's main organiser Drew Duffy added: "The fact that we have not received a clear response from the site supervisor about the needs of the company and the future investment plan in Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of many families worked here, and the employees come mostly from the local community and the Glasgow area, where working at the factory here is a critical pillar of decent employment in the area of high unemployment and social separation.
From a job, pay, and utility - and, despite the outlook for Brexit, risingest cost of living and falling slow production - the eastern part of Glasgow needs a desperately prosperous manufacturer like McVitie's."
A spokesperson for Pladis said: "The manager of Tollcross received a letter from GMB only yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible, as we value the continuing commitment to the employees and representatives of the unions.
A regular meeting with the staff and GMB representatives in Tollcross took place two months ago and there were openly discussed many of the problems at this meeting.
We were talking to employees that, as in all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we assess our operations on a regular basis, which is true for all of our operations so that we can continue to compete successfully with others.
To this she added: "In recent years, we have invested £5 million in the Tollcross area, particularly in production lines and streamlining of operations.
We are very much appreciative of the heritage of Tollcross and the site here, and in the event of any changes in the operation of the factory, the employees and representatives of the unions will be informed without delay."
